{"source_key":"sha256-3639711ec9037118dec0595de2c93477","record_index":264,"record_hash":"sha256:cbb8bc5afcff764b5cf313324b9880c726145602dba562f5bac189d75ad40ba9","timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:41:29.672Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"**Findings**\\n\\n[P1] Missing failed/partial environment test coverage.  \\nSpec says transcript capture must still write the turn when environment collection fails, with `snapshot_status = failed` or `partial` and coarse `error_kind` only. None of the new tests exercise [environment_from_parts](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:137) or failure paths from [capture_environment](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:117). Add narrow unit tests in `environment.rs` for: both unavailable => `failed`, worktree-only => `partial`, workspace with commit-file errors => `partial/diff_unavailable`. This is the biggest likely regression hole.\\n\\n[P1] `observed_targets` projection is barely tested.  \\nThe contract says `observed_targets` is a deterministic projection of `environment`, but [capture_turn_stores_branch_commit_and_change_observations](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:708) only checks that some change key starts with `gitbutler-change:`. It would pass if `observed_targets.changes` were unrelated to the stored commit snapshots. Add a test that extracts `environment.stacks[*].branches[*].commits[*].change_id` and asserts `observed_targets.changes` is exactly those keys after sort/dedup. Same idea for branch keys.\\n\\n[P2] Worktree test only covers an untracked file.  \\n[...worktree_paths](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:679) creates `src/lib.rs` in an empty repo, so it won’t catch a regression where tracked modifications disappear. The spec wants tracked and untracked uncommitted files. Make this test commit one file, modify it, add one untracked file, and assert both relative paths appear.\\n\\n[P2] Branch/commit test has a brittle JSON access pattern.  \\nAt [gitmeta.rs:743](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:743), the test indexes `branch[\\\"commits\\\"][0]` while iterating every branch. If the workspace snapshot grows an empty branch/segment before the target branch, this panics even if the behavior is fine. Flatten commits first, then search commit file lists. Same behavior, less incidental coupling.\\n\\n[P2] Summary/detail status consistency is untested.  \\nThe write path stores status in both [TurnSummary](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:48) and detail environment [gitmeta.rs:190](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:190). Current test only asserts summary status is not `\\\"failed\\\"` at [gitmeta.rs:701](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:701). Add `turns[0][\\\"environment_snapshot_status\\\"] == detail[\\\"environment\\\"][\\\"snapshot_status\\\"]`; tiny assertion, catches annoying timeline/detail drift.\\n\\nThe current tests do protect some real behavior: path capping/sort/dedup is good, root commit file capture gets some coverage, and the capture-level tests verify storage shape end-to-end. The weak spot is that the most important environment contract is best-effort behavior, and that’s exactly what isn’t locked down yet.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:41:29.672Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}